metadata.name: Alienpillars #28
metadata.description:
"A rare type of bug that supposedly arrived on a cargo ship is destroying crops on planet Uctumi, in the binary system of Extronium. A wide variety of very resistant subspecies has mutated and it is necessary to study and identify all of them to obtain a gen-activated pesticide that will work on all of their variations. The pest department of the Uctumi central government is working hard on it, and they say that these strange critters are probably related to similar species that inhabited the planet Earth of the Solar system a long time ago and have spread over the galaxy."

My second piece using the p5.js raymarcher I wrote. The drawing is made of circles and lines based on the 3D data. I wanted to try something hairy as it's easy to draw lines aligned to the surface normal with this method. I also used a shader for the frame and the glitchy/sketch features.

Features 

body color: green-red-purple-yellow-blue-black
body tone: dark-light
spots color: orange-green-blue-yellow-white
hair tips: yes-no
hair #1: short-medium-long
hair #2: short-medium-long
head size: small-medium-large
head shape: long-spherical-wide
glitchy mode: 10% chance
sketch mode: 9% chance

My previous Token "Patched" had an issue where different viewport sizes rendered slightly different outputs. At the time I was not able to correct this but now I am!

metadata.name: Simple_Syrup_1 #48
metadata.description:
Simple_Syrup_1, by Stephen Boyd
May, 2022
Little India, Toronto, Canada.


_Project Description
"The staple cocktail sweetener more than earns its name, consisting, simply, of equal-parts granulated sugar and water. From there, the variations are endless."
https://www.liquor.com/recipes/simple-syrup/


"The variations are endless..." I think of simple syrup as an analogy for what I've seen during my brief time so far on fxhash. The combination of a platform and people bringing out endless variations of creativity. Each Project with the possibility for endless variation in the exploration of a limited number of features.

This is my first project released on fxhash. I'm grateful to everyone who founded fxhash and to everyone who has positively contributed to the community.

These images are comprised of clusters of coloured ellipses on a coloured background. Each cluster varies in their strokeWeight, position, transparency and colour values.

There are two primary variables that all other features are dependent on: the first being the number of clusters, and the second is the number of ellipses in each cluster (up to a maximum of 123 per cluster). From these two variables the rest of the visual attributes (eg. alpha vs strokeWeight, colour palettes, etc...) are determined.

A constant in all my work, including this project, is the use of PHI and a Fibonnaci sequence starting with 4 and 7 to determine layouts and relationships between elements in the image. If you look through the code you will find many instances of the numbers: 4, 7, 11, 18, 29, 47,....

There are 18 colour palettes for this project. They are adapted from Mark Rothko paintings as interpreted by Merritt Smith, (https://mmerrittsmith.github.io/about/). I refactored the original R files to work with Javascript here. You can find Merritt's original project on GitHub: https://github.com/mmerrittsmith/rothko .


_Interaction
You can export this image to PNG format at several different sizes.

I've added code that will re-render the iteration at each of the sizes listed below while retaining its exact characteristics. This is considerably better than trying to up or downscale an image.

Press t: thumbnail @ 200x200 
Press s: your current screen size 
Press p: print size @ 4800x4800 which is 16"@300dpi 
Press h: HD4K on the vertical @ 2160x2160 
Press m: Max size @ 10800x10800 This is a biiiig size


_Technology Used for Development
Made with Processing / P5.js
p5.js v1.4.1 February 02, 2022

metadata.name: breken #6
metadata.description:
breken is a continued exploration of solid lines and primary colors.

I start with a random set of seed locations. Cracks spread out from these locations until reaching the edge of the square, or encountering another crack. The resulting polygons are then potentially scaled, rotated, and/or warped.

metadata.name: September #305
metadata.description:
The Summer Ends
---------------
Controls:
S or double tap (mobile): Download image

A: Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)

1-6: Modify scale (1 = default, 1500 x 2000px, 6 = maximum, 9000 x 12000px (performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F: Fit to current screen size

T: Toggle grain and texture overlay
H: Toggle shape outlines

B: Cycle border sizes (0 -> 50 -> 75 -> 100 -> 150px)
C: Cycle border colors

I: Cycle visible layers

L: Toggle “live mode”. This mode will continuously redraw a new output every few seconds using the same base parameters as the original output, but with slight variations.

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)

metadata.name: Tuesday #127
metadata.description: Maybe it's inspired by the marks left by coffee cups in my notebook. Maybe the doodles in that same notebook, often squares and circles, somehow influenced this work. Maybe the Bridget Riley book sitting on the shelf above gently whispered to me when I wasn't looking. Or maybe I just played with an idea and found it pleasing. The only thing I'm certain of – it was definitely a Tuesday.

metadata.name: Zhu(竹) #80
metadata.description:
Zhu(竹):

"Zhu" is a series of 100 oriental abstract pieces featuring the imagery of bamboo, a symbol of integrity and strength in traditional Chinese culture.

Zhu's generative system is an exploration of this cultural symbol by modern art language. Elements of the paintings are merely circles, enclosed flow field shapes, and the blank space behind these visual objects. Blank-leaving is intentionally applied at various degrees throughout the series. The vast empty space beyond the plants is open to and embraces every kind of interpretation.

Zhu's outputs span hours of the day from dawn to dusk to night. Its color schemes explored four styles from traditional to modern. The simple yet complex senses and feelings reflected are surprisingly versatile.

metadata.name: Sub Section Patina #128
metadata.description:
"Sub Section Patina" is inspired by street art and the marks and layering from that art form. If you zoom in on a small section of a wall that artists have marked, sprayed paint, and plastered with posters, some beautiful effects start to happen.

While the "Sub Section Patina" layers are building up, there is a tendency to destroy the layers below. The layering is similar to a wall many street artists have contributed. Sometimes just a section will be covered and filled with something else. Sometimes large areas of the canvas are covered up. Other layers will be put on top of one another, creating a new chaotic image. 

Features:
Four different sizes: 9x16, 11x14", 12x18", 12x12"
Portrait or landscape orientation
~500 color pallets, one black and white, one cyan, magenta, yellow and black, and the rest from Jam3/nice-color-palettes.

Dependencies:
processing/p5.js
lodash/lodash
Jam3/nice-color-palettes
substack/point-in-polygon

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (see features for dimensions)

License: CC-BY

Please find me on Twitter and Instagram at @natenolting.

metadata.name: Pastoral Palettes #74
metadata.description:
Pastoral Palettes showcases 93 beautiful hand tuned palettes in a generative pastoral setting. The palettes themselves pay homage to great paintings from the past up to the present. Isolating the palettes in this way brings out the artistic genius of the underlying artwork in a unique way. The palette name in the features contains the painting and artist.

The algorithmic parts of Pastoral Palettes use many techniques to create the scene and generate the ground, sky, trees, and shrubbery. Using random perlin noise for the placement ensures a more natural looking scene. The sky is a gradient composed from the palette. Each blade of grass is drawn individually using perlin noise to create the color pattern in the grass. Each tree and shrub is randomly constructed and colored using color blending in the transition colors. The grass generation is the most computationally expensive and the density can be adjusted with the arrow keys, see below.

The mint size is relatively small in relation to the number of palettes, so to ensure that all palettes get generated at least once, we are including 2 palettes for each mint.

Each mint of Pastoral Palettes comes with sunlight and moonlight views, toggled with the 'f' key. The palettes look strikingly different for each view - you can choose which one you like best.

Variations:

 - Each palette has an equal chance of being minted. Since the mint size is so small compared to the number of palettes, there is a high chance of getting a rare palette. 
 - 2% chance of getting 5 palettes instead of the default of 2. 
 - 10% chance of getting a sun/moon in the sky.
 - Each layout will be entirely unique.

Pastoral Palettes is responsive and looks great on any size display. They look especially good on large displays of 2K, 4K, and even 8K.

'f' flips between sunlight and moonlight views.
'p' cycles through the palettes.
's' saves an image in the exact size of the current display.
'up/down arrow' adjusts the grass density. Denser grass may look better at some resolutions, but takes considerably longer to render, particularly on large displays.
